{
  "texts": [
    "It is also important to emphasize that large-scale anticipation of emerging pests is a key element of integrated surveillance, as it helps to define what to monitor, where and when.",
    "By profiling their environmental, life-history traits and adaptive characteristics, potential emerging pests can be identified.",
    "The risk of pest outbreaks in a given region can be predicted, and thus anticipated, by matching the environmental preferences of species that have been documented as problematic elsewhere and formalized in a knowledge base, with the environmental conditions in the region of interest.",
    "This approach, known as species distribution modeling (SDM; Zurell et al. 2020), involves the use of statistical models to relate the occurrence of the species of interest to large-scale environmental gradients in both native and invaded areas.",
    "The potential distribution of the species in the region of interest can then be projected under current environmental conditions, or under scenarios of climate, land use or cropping system changes (Bebber et al. 2013; Matzrafi et al. 2019)."
  ]
}